        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>London</placeName> <date>17th Adar <add>&#63;</add> 5611</date></p>
          <p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee> <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Revd. and Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">I had the pleasure of receiving yours of the <date>4th&#58;<lb/> March</date> on <date>Purim</date> day you will see that however I may be situated I do<lb/> not allow a post to let your subject unnoticed&#59; of course I can say but<lb/> little this day since I wrote to you on <date><sic>friday</sic></date> last&#44; neither have I<lb/> had any reply to my second letter which I addressed <persName>Mr. A. Hart</persName><lb/> on the <date>19&#58;th Adar</date>&#44; the moment I do&#44; you shall be made acquainted<lb/> with the contents trusting &#38; hoping <hi rend="underline">good</hi> <add>Hebrew</add> I noticed in yours wherein you<lb/> say &#34;as <persName>Mr. A&#58; Hart</persName> denies having commissioned anyone to speak to<lb/> <persName>Mr. Morais.</persName>&#34; I trust &#38; hope you will see to this point seriously&#44; that<lb/> <persName>Mr. M&#39;s</persName> name will not be brought to question in any way particularly mine in<lb/> the slightest way do I wish it&#44; for whatever I communicated to you was<lb/> in the strictest confidence and so <persName><hi rend="underline">did <persName>Morais</persName></hi></persName> when he opened his mind<lb/> to me as a <hi rend="underline">friend</hi>&#44; relying on my honor he related to me the whole<lb/> from a beginning&#59; now to the best of my recollection&#44; I <sic>dont</sic> think this lady<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> <persName>Mr. <hi rend="underline">A&#58; Hart</hi></persName> but &#34;she should write about it to a <persName>Mr. Hart.</persName>&#34; neither<lb/> was her commission <hi rend="underline">direct</hi> to <persName>Mr. M</persName>&#44; she spoke to him on her having heard<lb/> him and thought he would do&#44; but she was looking <hi rend="underline">for some one</hi> as<lb/> they were in want of a Hazan&#44; therefore pray do not let me have<lb/> any more to do with that lady <persName>Mrs. Claudia</persName>&#44; nor do not allow our<lb/> name to be mingled any further. I wish to be clear with <persName>Mr. M</persName>&#58;<lb/> and do not wish him to think in the least that I caused through my<lb/> correspondence the slightest confession I <hi rend="underline">rely</hi> on <hi rend="underline">you</hi> to this&#44; for things are<lb/> taken in so many views when there are so many parties all <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> pray neither expose any further the conduct of that lady towards me&#44; for one</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>thing may stir the other. I delivered myself of our letter to <persName>Mr. Peynado</persName><lb/> he was very thankful to me. I return you my <add>&#63;</add> thanks for<lb/> your valuable and truly precious present I will write to you on this<lb/> on another occasion as I am a little disturbed this day my mind<lb/> is not adequate to write as I should <add>&#63;</add> in any way you think me<lb/> capable of serving you pray do not hesitate in the least as I shall<lb/> ever consider it a pleasure. I shall not forget your commission.<lb/> Wishing you most heartily to be the successful <add>&#63;</add> and that all<lb/> your friends will support and uphold your <hi rend="underline">just cause</hi>. I do not make<lb/> any observations on the other points you wrote concerning <persName>Bowenfeld</persName> &#38;c<lb/> <persName>Dr. Raphael</persName> style &#38;c which I have much to say &#40;and will do it&#41; for<lb/> the cause I have assigned. I <hi rend="underline">hinted</hi> it to <persName>Morais</persName> to mind what he did<lb/> I could not press much upon him as he might suppose it was <add>&#63;</add><lb/> sake he has obtained permission for 3 months from the school he teaches<lb/> and I believe some friends made him assume to defray all expenses<lb/> no doubt against this reaches you he must have had his trial<lb/> I shall be glad to hear the result our friend <persName>Mr. Isaacs</persName> lectures<lb/> tomorrow morning at the new synagogue I have not seen him since<lb/> his return from <placeName>Holland</placeName> <add>Hebrew</add>&#44; I remain with all esteem &#38; regard</p>
			<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
          <p rend="indent(6)">Revd. &#38; dear sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(6)">yours very faithfully</p>
          <p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">David Meldola</persName></p>
			<p>We must bear in mind that perhaps when<lb/> the lady sent for <persName>Morais</persName> it might have been in confidence therefore<lb/> I should not like on my part to betray the confidence of a friend.<lb/> <persName>Rabbi Nissim</persName> always enquires in his letters about your affairs.</p>
          
        </body>
